# Backend trust boundary

Align with `docs/SECURITY.md` (Core Principles, Authentication, Authorization & Ownership, Privacy, Input Validation, API Security, Rate Limiting) and `docs/BACKEND.md`.

**Frontend improves UX; the backend enforces security.** Client-side checks are optional hints only—they are not authorization, validation, privacy, or abuse control.

## Enforce on the server

| Concern | Backend must |
|--------|----------------|
| **Authentication** | Verify session/token on every protected request; never trust a client-supplied `userId` as proof of identity. |
| **Ownership (IDOR)** | Resolve the actor from the session, then scope reads/writes by that user (or explicit public rules). Resource IDs from the client never grant access by themselves. |
| **Input validation** | Validate and constrain bodies/params (types, ranges, allowed enums, dates). Reject invalid input before persistence. |
| **Privacy** | Filter responses and queries so private data (e.g. reflections, hidden fields) never leaks through “convenient” APIs. |
| **Rate limiting** | Apply limits server-side (per user/IP as in docs); clients cannot bypass them. |

## Quick checks

- [ ] Handler assumes **no** trust in client identity or “already validated” payloads.
- [ ] Mutations check **ownership** (or documented public behavior) in the same layer that talks to the DB.
- [ ] Responses include only **least data** needed; errors are safe (no secrets, no stack traces to clients).

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — identity and access from the body
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const { userId, bookId } = await req.json();
  await db.books.update(bookId, { ... }); // anyone could pass another userId/bookId
}

// ✅ GOOD — identity from verified session; access via ownership
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const session = await getSession(req);
  if (!session) return Response.json({ error: "Unauthorized" }, { status: 401 });
  const body = parseAndValidateBookUpdate(await req.json()); // server schema
  const book = await db.books.findFirst({ id: body.bookId, userId: session.userId });
  if (!book) return Response.json({ error: "Not found" }, { status: 404 });
  await db.books.update(book.id, body.patch);
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — “we already validated in React”
if (pagesRead >= 1 && pagesRead <= 1000) save(pagesRead); // only in browser

// ✅ GOOD — same rules enforced in the API / server action
const pagesRead = bookUpdateSchema.parse(body).pagesRead; // reject if out of range
```

